{"questionId":"12166","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>This question investigates some applications of differential equations to modeling population growth.</p>\n<p>One model for population growth is to assume that the rate of change of the population is proportional to the population, i.e.&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{{\\text{d}}P}}{{{\\text{d}}t}} = kP\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>d</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mi>P</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>d</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mi>t</mi>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mi>P</mi>\n</math></span>, where&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"k \\in \\mathbb{R}\">\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"t\">\n  <mi>t</mi>\n</math></span> is the time (in years) and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P\">\n  <mi>P</mi>\n</math></span> is the population</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The initial population is 1000.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider now the situation when <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"k\">\n  <mi>k</mi>\n</math></span> is not a constant, but a function of time.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Another model for population growth assumes</p>\n<ul>\n<li>there is a maximum value for the population, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"L\">\n  <mi>L</mi>\n</math></span>.</li>\n<li>that&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"k\">\n  <mi>k</mi>\n</math></span> is not a constant, but is proportional to <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\left( {1 - \\frac{P}{L}} \\right)\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mfrac>\n        <mi>P</mi>\n        <mi>L</mi>\n      </mfrac>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</li>\n</ul></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Given that the initial population is 1000, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"L&nbsp;= 10000\"> <mi>L</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>10000</mn> </math></span>&nbsp; and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"m = 0.003\"> <mi>m</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0.003</mn> </math></span>, find the number of years it will take for the population to triple.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"1000 = \\frac{{10000}}{{D + 1}}\"> <mn>1000</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>10000</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>D</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"D = 9\"> <mi>D</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>9</mn> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"3000 = \\frac{{10000}}{{9{e^{ - 0.003t}} + 1}}\"> <mn>3000</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>10000</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>9</mn> <mrow> <msup> <mi>e</mi> <mrow> <mo>−</mo> <mn>0.003</mn> <mi>t</mi> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"t = 450\"> <mi>t</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>450</mn> </math></span> years&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"12166","referenceCode":"EXM.3.AHL.TZ0.4f","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Given that the initial population is 1000, L = 10000 and m = 0.003 , find the number of years it will take for the population to triple.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"f","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.18—1st order DE’s – Euler method, variables separable, integrating factor, homogeneous DE using sub y=vx","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.11—Partial fractions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}